    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1987-04-18T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1987-04-18T00:00:00-05:00" n="297"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d297">
                <head>297. Memorandum From the President’s Assistant for National Security Affairs
                        (<persName corresp="#p_CFC_1">Carlucci</persName>) to President <persName
                        corresp="#p_RRW_1">Reagan</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d297fn1">Source: Reagan Library, <persName
                            corresp="#p_CFC_1">Frank Carlucci</persName> Files, <persName
                            corresp="#p_BHH_1">Howard Baker</persName> (03/27/1987–04/28/1987;
                        NLR–776–B1–2–2–1–6. Confidential. Sent for information. Copies were sent to
                            <persName corresp="#p_BHH_1">Howard Baker</persName> and <persName
                            corresp="#p_SGP_1">Shultz</persName>. Also printed in <ref
                            target="frus1981-88v06#d50">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1981–1988, vol. VI, Soviet
                            Union, October 1986–January 1989, Document 50</ref>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1987-04-18">April 18, 1987</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SGP_1">Shultz</persName> Moscow Visit</item>
                </list>
                <p>I have briefed Former Presidents <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName>,
                        <persName corresp="#p_FGR_1">Ford</persName> and <persName
                        corresp="#p_NRM_1">Nixon</persName> on the <persName corresp="#p_SGP_1"
                        >Shultz</persName> Moscow Visit.<note n="2" xml:id="d297fn2">See <ref
                            target="#d292fn4">footnote 4, Document 292</ref>.</note> All appreciated
                    the contact.</p>
                <p>President <persName corresp="#p_FGR_1">Ford</persName> laid particular emphasis
                    on not allowing the Soviets to place any constraints on <gloss target="#t_SDI_1"
                        >SDI</gloss>
                    <rs corresp="recAWJwqRIM3ZNS4f" type="topic">deployment</rs>. President
                        <persName corresp="#p_NRM_1">Nixon</persName> was not surprised that little
                    progress had been made in the <gloss target="#t_START_1">START</gloss> Space and
                    Defense area. He expressed concern about the Zero <gloss target="#t_SRINF_1"
                        >SRINF</gloss> proposal. While politically it is hard for the Europeans to
                    refuse such a proposal, he noted, it does entail a rupture “in the seamless web”
                    of the <gloss target="#t_NATO_1">NATO</gloss> flexible response doctrine.
                    Europeans worry that acceptance of the Zero option would move us closer to a
                    massive retaliation response to a Soviet attack in Europe where we would be in
                    the position of “trading Cleveland for Berlin.”</p>
                <p>President <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName> was supportive of the
                        <gloss target="#t_INF_1">INF</gloss> initiative, including the Zero <gloss
                        target="#t_SRINF_1">SRINF</gloss> proposal. He said he would so state
                    publicly if you desired.</p>
                <p>I also talked to <persName corresp="#p_BZK_1">Zbignew Brzezinski</persName> who
                    was quite supportive of our approach, although he acknowledged the concerns of
                    the Europeans. He raised one caution and one suggestion. We should avoid getting
                    into the Carter trap whereby we raise expectations on a treaty and a summit to
                    the point where we generate pressure on ourselves to make unwise concessions.
                    The suggestion was that we consider a dramatic new proposal on conventional
                    reductions.</p>
            </div>
